    <title>Combined summary - BIP Proposal: Revised: UTPFOTIB - Use Transaction Priority For Ordering Transactions In Blocks</title>
    <updated>2023-06-12T22:57:27.184517+00:00</updated>
    <link href="https://lists.linuxfoundation.org/pipermail/bitcoin-dev/2017-December/015417.html" rel="alternate"/>
    <summary>Bitcoin developer Damian Williamson has proposed a new Bitcoin Improvement Proposal (BIP) called "UTPFOTIB" to address the issue of transactional reliability in Bitcoin. The proposal involves assigning a transaction priority to each valid transaction in the mempool based on the fee paid and time waiting in the transaction pool, and selecting transactions to include in the current block using probability until the target block size is met. The aim is to maximize transaction reliability, overcome transaction bandwidth limit, be fully scalable, and maximize total fees paid per block without reducing reliability. However, there are concerns about its feasibility and potential for miners to cheat.Williamson's proposal needs further development and feedback to make it a full BIP. Verification of blocks conforming to the proposal may be possible by showing statistically that all transactions included in the block conform to a probability distribution curve. Additionally, a revised BIP was proposed in January 2018, which suggests using a market-determined fee for transaction priority, dynamic block sizes that are scalable, and a probability distribution curve to verify all blocks created with dynamic size. The proposal aims to create a more stable and reliable service that will have greater consumer and business acceptance and is in miners' financial interest.There are concerns about the technical implementation and fundamental errors of these proposals, as well as miners cheating and ignoring the proposal's prioritization of transactions based on fees. Nevertheless, ongoing discussions on the mailing list highlight efforts to improve the scalability and reliability of the Bitcoin system. A reliable permanent solution is required to provide transaction confirmation services for all transactions and maintain consumer acceptance. The proposed changes aim to validate full transaction reliability and enable scalability of block sizes.</summary>
